        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> The random gibberish inserted into the buffer on startup, usually is caused by your GUI terminal not understanding a termcode sequence which Nvim emits on startup. Nvim 0.12 emits requests for RGB support, bg color detection, etc.\n> \n> This behavior is almost always a bug in the terminal, and in this case, based on other reports, it's very likely a bug in the old Win10 terminal.\n> \n> similar:\n> \n> * [TUI: bg color response consumed as user input (inserts \"g\", \"0000/2b2b/3636^G\") #11393](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/11393)\n> * [Garbage typed when starting Neovim in Alacritty #10131](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/10131)\n> \n> ## Workaround\n> * As a workaround you can use `nvim -u NONE` .\n> * We are also exploring a way to disable the \"terminal feature detection\" (which involves sending the termcode sequences mentioned above): [feat(startup): restore ttyfast to control startup behavior #38699](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/38699)\n\nOh, nice.\n\nI change it like this:\n@=\"\"C:\\Program Files\\Neovim\\bin\\nvim.exe\" -u NONE \"%1\"\"\nGreat, everything seems to be fine now.",
